  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Property prices are ultimately set by what buyers can and will pay. One of the most significant variables in that equation is borrowing capacity: the maximum a buyer can borrow from a lender given their income, expenses, existing debt, and the current interest rate environment. Understanding how borrowing capacity works gives sellers a more grounded basis for pricing decisions than simply watching what comparable properties sold for six or twelve months ago.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How lenders assess borrowing capacity</h2>
      <p>Australian lenders assess whether a borrower can service a loan not at the actual rate they would pay, but at a higher rate called a serviceability buffer. The Australian Prudential Regulation Authority (APRA) requires lenders to assess serviceability at the current interest rate plus a minimum 3% buffer. This means a buyer seeking a loan at a rate of 6% is assessed as if they were paying 9%.</p>

      <p>The buffer exists to ensure borrowers are not placed under financial stress if rates increase after settlement. The practical effect is that buyers can borrow significantly less than they might expect based on current repayment figures alone. The buffer has a larger impact at higher base rates, because the assessed rate at which income is tested becomes correspondingly higher.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to borrowing capacity when rates rise</h2>
      <p>A rise in the cash rate flows through to mortgage rates and reduces what buyers can borrow. As a rough guide, a 1% increase in the cash rate reduces average borrowing capacity by approximately 10%. On a property in the $1 million to $1.5 million range, that translates to a meaningful reduction in what the buyer pool can finance.</p>

      <p>When borrowing capacity falls, the pool of buyers who can finance a property at a given price point shrinks. Fewer buyers competing for the same property means fewer offers, longer days on market, and reduced upward pressure on price. Sellers who price based on what the market looked like before a rate cycle may find their listing attracts less attention than expected, not because the property is overpriced relative to what it was worth previously, but because the buyer pool has contracted.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens when rates fall</h2>
      <p>The reverse applies when rates fall. A reduction in the cash rate increases what buyers can borrow, which expands the pool of buyers who can finance a property at a given price. More buyers in the market means more competition, shorter campaigns, and stronger pricing. Sellers who list during a period of falling rates typically benefit from improved conditions even if the headline price environment has not yet visibly shifted.</p>

      <p>Rate cuts also tend to improve buyer sentiment, which affects how confidently buyers bid at auction and how quickly they move to make offers in private treaty campaigns. Sentiment and borrowing capacity often move together, which is why periods of falling rates can produce quite rapid changes in market conditions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which buyers are most affected</h2>
      <p>Not all buyers are equally sensitive to interest rate movements. First home buyers and highly leveraged purchasers, who are borrowing close to their maximum capacity, are the most affected when rates rise. A rate increase that reduces their borrowing capacity by $100,000 may move a property from affordable to out of reach entirely.</p>

      <p>Buyers who have significant equity from a previous sale, cash buyers, and downsizers selling a larger property and buying a smaller one are less affected by rate movements. This is relevant to Brisbane's inner-east market, which has a high proportion of owner-occupier buyers upgrading or right-sizing within the area. These buyers are somewhat more resilient to rate pressure than the overall buyer population, which is worth factoring into how you read local conditions versus national headlines.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to apply this as a seller</h2>
      <p>The practical takeaway for sellers is that pricing a property based on what comparable properties sold for at a different point in the rate cycle can produce misleading expectations. A sale that occurred 12 months earlier in a lower-rate environment may have attracted buyers who can no longer finance the same amount today. The property's intrinsic value has not necessarily changed, but the population of buyers who can access it at a given price has.</p>

      <p>Before settling on a price expectation, it is worth understanding current borrowing capacity in your price range. A good agent will show you what a buyer with a particular income can realistically borrow at current rates, and can map that against the buyer profile your property is likely to attract. That gives you a more accurate picture of where the effective ceiling is for your campaign than headline figures from previous sales in different market conditions.</p>

      <p>It also shapes campaign strategy. In a rate-constrained market where borrowing capacity is compressed, private treaty with price transparency may outperform auction, because buyers who are near their limit need more certainty before committing to a campaign spend. In a falling-rate environment with expanding capacity, auction conditions may be more competitive and better suited to capturing the upside from renewed buyer confidence.</p>

